aa(lp51
VSo I'd like to start with a little bit of history on the project.
p52
aVThis is based on an F. Scott Fitzgerald short story.
p53
aVIt's about a man who's born old and lives his life in reverse.
p54
aVNow, this movie has floated around Hollywood
p55
aVfor well over half a century,
p56
aVand we first got involved with the project in the early '90s,
p57
aVwith Ron Howard as the director.
p58
aVWe took a lot of meetings and we seriously considered it.
p59
aVBut at the time we had to throw in the towel.
p60
aVIt was deemed impossible.
p61
aVIt was beyond the technology of the day to depict a man aging backwards.
p62
aVThe human form, in particular the human head,
p63
aVhas been considered the Holy Grail of our industry.
p64
aa(lp65
VThe project came back to us about a decade later,
p66
aVand this time with a director named David Fincher.
p67
aVNow, Fincher is an interesting guy.
p68
aVDavid is fearless of technology,
p69
aVand he is absolutely tenacious.
p70
aVAnd David won't take "no."
p71
aVAnd David believed, like we do in the visual effects industry,
p72
aVthat anything is possible
p73
aVas long as you have enough time, resources and, of course, money.
p74
aVAnd so David had an interesting take on the film,
p75
aVand he threw a challenge at us.
p76
aVHe wanted the main character of the film to be played
p77
aVfrom the cradle to the grave by one actor.
p78
aVIt happened to be this guy.
p79
aa(lp80
VWe went through a process of elimination and a process of discovery
p81
aVwith David, and we ruled out, of course, swapping actors.
p82
aVThat was one idea: that we would have different actors,
p83
aVand we would hand off from actor to actor.
p84
aa(lp85
VWe even ruled out the idea of using makeup.
p86
aVWe realized that prosthetic makeup just wouldn't hold up,
p87
aVparticularly in close-up.
p88
aVAnd makeup is an additive process. You have to build the face up.
p89
aVAnd David wanted to carve deeply into Brad's face
p90
aVto bring the aging to this character.
p91
aVHe needed to be a very sympathetic character.
p92
aVSo we decided to cast a series of little people
p93
aVthat would play the different bodies of Benjamin
p94
aVat the different increments of his life
p95
aVand that we would in fact create a computer-generated version of Brad's head,
p96
aVaged to appear as Benjamin,
p97
aVand attach that to the body of the real actor.
p98
aVSounded great.
p99
aa(lp100
VOf course, this was the Holy Grail of our industry,
p101
aVand the fact that this guy is a global icon didn't help either,
p102
aVbecause I'm sure if any of you ever stand in line at the grocery store,
p103
aVyou know \u2014 we see his face constantly.
p104
aVSo there really was no tolerable margin of error.
p105
aVThere were two studios involved: Warner Brothers and Paramount.
p106
aVAnd they both believed this would make an amazing film, of course,
p107
aVbut it was a very high-risk proposition.
p108
aVThere was lots of money and reputations at stake.
p109
aVBut we believed that we had a very solid methodology
p110
aVthat might work ...
p111
aa(lp112
VBut despite our verbal assurances,
p113
aVthey wanted some proof.
p114
aVAnd so, in 2004, they commissioned us to do a screen test of Benjamin.
p115
aVAnd we did it in about five weeks.
p116
aVBut we used lots of cheats and shortcuts.
p117
aVWe basically put something together to get through the meeting.
p118
aVI'll roll that for you now. This was the first test for Benjamin Button.
p119
aVAnd in here, you can see, that's a computer-generated head \u2014
p120
aVpretty good \u2014 attached to the body of an actor.
p121
aVAnd it worked. And it gave the studio great relief.
p122
aVAfter many years of starts and stops on this project,
p123
aVand making that tough decision,
p124
aVthey finally decided to greenlight the movie.
p125
aVAnd I can remember, actually, when I got the phone call to congratulate us,
p126
aVto say the movie was a go,
p127
aVI actually threw up.
p128
aV(Laughter)
p129
aVYou know, this is some tough stuff.
