aa(lp131
VSo we started to have early team meetings,
p132
aVand we got everybody together,
p133
aVand it was really more like therapy in the beginning,
p134
aVconvincing each other and reassuring each other that we could actually undertake this.
p135
aVWe had to hold up an hour of a movie with a character.
p136
aVAnd it's not a special effects film; it has to be a man.
p137
aVWe really felt like we were in a \u2014 kind of a 12-step program.
p138
aVAnd of course, the first step is: admit you've got a problem. (Laughter)
p139
aVSo we had a big problem:
p140
aVwe didn't know how we were going to do this.
p141
aVBut we did know one thing.
p142
aVBeing from the visual effects industry,
p143
aVwe, with David, believed that we now had enough time,
p144
aVenough resources, and, God, we hoped we had enough money.
p145
aVAnd we had enough passion to will the processes and technology into existence.
p146
aa(lp147
VSo, when you're faced with something like that,
p148
aVof course you've got to break it down.
p149
aVYou take the big problem and you break it down into smaller pieces
p150
aVand you start to attack that.
p151
aVSo we had three main areas that we had to focus on.
p152
aVWe needed to make Brad look a lot older \u2014
p153
aVneeded to age him 45 years or so.
p154
aVAnd we also needed to make sure that we could take Brad's idiosyncrasies,
p155
aVhis little tics, the little subtleties that make him who he is
p156
aVand have that translate through our process
p157
aVso that it appears in Benjamin on the screen.
p158
aa(lp159
VAnd we also needed to create a character
p160
aVthat could hold up under, really, all conditions.
p161
aVHe needed to be able to walk in broad daylight,
p162
aVat nighttime, under candlelight,
p163
aVhe had to hold an extreme close-up,
p164
aVhe had to deliver dialogue,
p165
aVhe had to be able to run, he had to be able to sweat,
p166
aVhe had to be able to take a bath, to cry,
p167
aVhe even had to throw up.
p168
aVNot all at the same time \u2014
p169
aVbut he had to, you know, do all of those things.
p170
aa(lp171
VAnd the work had to hold up for almost the first hour of the movie.
p172
aVWe did about 325 shots.
p173
aVSo we needed a system that would allow Benjamin
p174
aVto do everything a human being can do.
p175
aVAnd we realized that there was a giant chasm
p176
aVbetween the state of the art of technology in 2004
p177
aVand where we needed it to be.
p178
aa(lp179
VSo we focused on motion capture.
p180
aVI'm sure many of you have seen motion capture.
p181
aVThe state of the art at the time
p182
aVwas something called marker-based motion capture.
p183
aVI'll give you an example here.
p184
aVIt's basically the idea of, you wear a leotard,
p185
aVand they put some reflective markers on your body,
p186
aVand instead of using cameras,
p187
aVthere're infrared sensors around a volume,
p188
aVand those infrared sensors track the three-dimensional position
p189
aVof those markers in real time.
p190
aVAnd then animators can take the data of the motion of those markers
p191
aVand apply them to a computer-generated character.
p192
aVYou can see the computer characters on the right
p193
aVare having the same complex motion as the dancers.
p194
aa(lp195
VBut we also looked at numbers of other films at the time
p196
aVthat were using facial marker tracking,
p197
aVand that's the idea of putting markers on the human face
p198
aVand doing the same process.
p199
aVAnd as you can see, it gives you a pretty crappy performance.
p200
aVThat's not terribly compelling.
p201
aVAnd what we realized
p202
aVwas that what we needed
p203
aVwas the information that was going on between the markers.
p204
aVWe needed the subtleties of the skin.
p205
aVWe needed to see skin moving over muscle moving over bone.
p206
aVWe needed creases and dimples and wrinkles and all of those things.
p207
aa(lp208
VOur first revelation was to completely abort and walk away from
p209
aVthe technology of the day, the status quo, the state of the art.
p210
aVSo we aborted using motion capture.
p211
aVAnd we were now well out of our comfort zone,
p212
aVand in uncharted territory.
p213
aVSo we were left with this idea
p214
aVthat we ended up calling "technology stew."
p215
aVWe started to look out in other fields.
p216
aVThe idea was that we were going to find
p217
aVnuggets or gems of technology
p218
aVthat come from other industries like medical imaging,
p219
aVthe video game space,
p220
aVand re-appropriate them.
p221
aVAnd we had to create kind of a sauce.
p222
aVAnd the sauce was code in software
p223
aVthat we'd written to allow these disparate pieces of technology
p224
aVto come together and work as one.
p225
aa(lp226
VInitially, we came across some remarkable research
p227
aVdone by a gentleman named Dr. Paul Ekman in the early '70s.
p228
aVHe believed that he could, in fact,
p229
aVcatalog the human face.
p230
aVAnd he came up with this idea of Facial Action Coding System, or FACS.
p231
aVHe believed that there were 70 basic poses
p232
aVor shapes of the human face,
p233
aVand that those basic poses or shapes of the face
p234
aVcan be combined to create infinite possibilities
p235
aVof everything the human face is capable of doing.
p236
aVAnd of course, these transcend age, race, culture, gender.
p237
aVSo this became the foundation of our research as we went forward.
p238
aa(lp239
VAnd then we came across some remarkable technology
p240
aVcalled Contour.
p241
aVAnd here you can see a subject having phosphorus makeup
p242
aVstippled on her face.
p243
aVAnd now what we're looking at is really creating a surface capture
p244
aVas opposed to a marker capture.
p245
aVThe subject stands in front of a computer array of cameras,
p246
aVand those cameras can, frame-by-frame,
p247
aVreconstruct the geometry of exactly what the subject's doing at the moment.
p248
aVSo, effectively, you get 3D data in real time of the subject.
p249
aVAnd if you look in a comparison,
p250
aVon the left, we see what volumetric data gives us
p251
aVand on the right you see what markers give us.
p252
aVSo, clearly, we were in a substantially better place for this.
p253
aVBut these were the early days of this technology,
p254
aVand it wasn't really proven yet.
p255
aVWe measure complexity and fidelity of data
p256
aVin terms of polygonal count.
p257
aVAnd so, on the left, we were seeing 100,000 polygons.
p258
aVWe could go up into the millions of polygons.
p259
aVIt seemed to be infinite.
p260
aa(lp261
VThis was when we had our "Aha!"
p262
aVThis was the breakthrough.
p263
aVThis is when we're like, "OK, we're going to be OK,
p264
aVThis is actually going to work."
p265
aVAnd the "Aha!" was, what if we could take Brad Pitt,
p266
aVand we could put Brad in this device,
p267
aVand use this Contour process,
p268
aVand we could stipple on this phosphorescent makeup
p269
aVand put him under the black lights,
p270
aVand we could, in fact, scan him in real time
p271
aVperforming Ekman's FACS poses.
p272
aVRight? So, effectively,
p273
aVwe ended up with a 3D database
p274
aVof everything Brad Pitt's face is capable of doing.
p275
aV(Laughter)
p276
aa(lp277
VFrom there, we actually carved up those faces
p278
aVinto smaller pieces and components of his face.
p279
aVSo we ended up with literally thousands and thousands and thousands of shapes,
p280
aVa complete database of all possibilities
p281
aVthat his face is capable of doing.
